{"info": {"author": "Tommaso De Rossi", "author_email": "daer.tommy@gmail.com", "bugtrack_url": null, "classifiers": ["Intended Audience :: Information Technology", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.6", "Programming Language :: Python :: 3.7"], "description": "# compose-watcher\n\n<p align=\"center\">\n    <img src='https://raw.githubusercontent.com/remorses/compose-watcher/master/.github/compose_watcher_video.gif'>\n</p>\n\nCli that restarts you docker compose services when a file inside one of its volumes changes.\n\nUseful for faster developement with containers that expose behaviour based on mounted files.\n\nExample usage\n\n-   graphql api restart when schema file changes\n-   graphql api mocks based on schema file ([like this one](https://github.com/remorses/graphql-easy-mocks))\n-   Every container that generates code and exposes a server based on a config file\n-   Nodejs container restarts when the src folder changes, recompiling with tsc\n-   [Mongoke](https://github.com/remorses/mongoke) restarts when config schema changes\n\n## Install\n\n```sh\npip3 install compose-watcher\n# then you can watch for changes\ncompose-watcher -f docker-compose.yml\n```\n\n## Usage\n\nUse the directories you want to track as service volumes.\n\nAlso consider using `init: true` in the compose service definition for faster killing of processes.\n\nTo not stop the `docker-compose` commands on other terminals there should be always a running container (this is a strange fact about docker-compose).\n\n```\nversion: '3'\n\nservices:\n  api:\n    build: .\n    command: sh -c 'tsc --incremental && node index.js'\n    volumes:\n      - ./src:/src\n\n```\n\nThen execute `compose-watcher` to watch changes.\n\n```sh\ncompose-watcher -f docker-compose.yml --timeout 5\n```\n\nTODO add extension filter\n\n## How it works\n\nAfter running the `compose-watcher` command all the volumes mounted on every service are tracked for change, when a change happens the service where the volume is mounted is restarted toghether with the services in the `depends_on` filed. Then the other services that have the restarted service as a dependency in `depends_on` are restarted too.", "description_content_type": "text/markdown", "docs_url": null, "download_url": "", "downloads": {"last_day": -1, "last_month": -1, "last_week": -1}, "home_page": "https://github.com/remorses/compose-watcher", "keywords": "docker-compose,watcher,watch", "license": "Apache Software License 2.0", "maintainer": "", "maintainer_email": "", "name": "compose-watcher", "package_url": "https://pypi.org/project/compose-watcher/", "platform": "", "project_url": "https://pypi.org/project/compose-watcher/", "project_urls": {"Homepage": "https://github.com/remorses/compose-watcher"}, "release_url": "https://pypi.org/project/compose-watcher/1.2.5/", "requires_dist": null, "requires_python": "", "summary": "compose-watcher", "version": "1.2.5", "yanked": false, "html_description": "<div class=\"project-description\">\n            <h1>compose-watcher</h1>\n<p align=\"center\">\n    <img src=\"https://warehouse-camo.ingress.cmh1.psfhosted.org/c24e5b64467901cb05eeff505c8d6ce0663958c7/68747470733a2f2f7261772e67697468756275736572636f6e74656e742e636f6d2f72656d6f727365732f636f6d706f73652d776174636865722f6d61737465722f2e6769746875622f636f6d706f73655f776174636865725f766964656f2e676966\">\n</p>\n<p>Cli that restarts you docker compose services when a file inside one of its volumes changes.</p>\n<p>Useful for faster developement with containers that expose behaviour based on mounted files.</p>\n<p>Example usage</p>\n<ul>\n<li>graphql api restart when schema file changes</li>\n<li>graphql api mocks based on schema file (<a href=\"https://github.com/remorses/graphql-easy-mocks\" rel=\"nofollow\">like this one</a>)</li>\n<li>Every container that generates code and exposes a server based on a config file</li>\n<li>Nodejs container restarts when the src folder changes, recompiling with tsc</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://github.com/remorses/mongoke\" rel=\"nofollow\">Mongoke</a> restarts when config schema changes</li>\n</ul>\n<h2>Install</h2>\n<pre>pip3 install compose-watcher\n<span class=\"c1\"># then you can watch for changes</span>\ncompose-watcher -f docker-compose.yml\n</pre>\n<h2>Usage</h2>\n<p>Use the directories you want to track as service volumes.</p>\n<p>Also consider using <code>init: true</code> in the compose service definition for faster killing of processes.</p>\n<p>To not stop the <code>docker-compose</code> commands on other terminals there should be always a running container (this is a strange fact about docker-compose).</p>\n<pre><code>version: '3'\n\nservices:\n  api:\n    build: .\n    command: sh -c 'tsc --incremental &amp;&amp; node index.js'\n    volumes:\n      - ./src:/src\n\n</code></pre>\n<p>Then execute <code>compose-watcher</code> to watch changes.</p>\n<pre>compose-watcher -f docker-compose.yml --timeout <span class=\"m\">5</span>\n</pre>\n<p>TODO add extension filter</p>\n<h2>How it works</h2>\n<p>After running the <code>compose-watcher</code> command all the volumes mounted on every service are tracked for change, when a change happens the service where the volume is mounted is restarted toghether with the services in the <code>depends_on</code> filed. Then the other services that have the restarted service as a dependency in <code>depends_on</code> are restarted too.</p>\n\n          </div>"}, "last_serial": 6843663, "releases": {"1.0.1": [{"comment_text": "", "digests": {"md5": "6ad6426b9b334430be029e0004dcca81", "sha256": "e737055d0662385b13040646da1bd67aa0dbb2302f2dc7f5a7aa7bc485e4c241"}, "downloads": -1, "filename": "compose-watcher-1.0.1.tar.gz", "has_sig": false, "md5_digest": "6ad6426b9b334430be029e0004dcca81", "packagetype": "sdist", "python_version": "source", "requires_python": null, "size": 3970, "upload_time": "2020-03-14T12:25:40", "upload_time_iso_8601": "2020-03-14T12:25:40.982188Z", "url":